(3, 'Europa', 110, 'Europa /jʊˈroʊpə/ (Jupiter II), is the sixth-closest moon of Jupiter, and the smallest of its four Galilean satellites, but still the sixth-largest moon in the Solar System. Europa was discovered in 1610 by Galileo Galilei[1] and was named after Europa, daughter of the king of Tyre, who became one of Zeus'' lovers. Progressively better observations of Europa have occurred over the centuries by Earth-bound telescopes, and by space probe flybys starting in the 1970s.\r\n\r\n<p>Slightly smaller than the Moon, Europa is primarily made of silicate rock and has a water-ice crust and probably an iron–nickel core. It has a tenuous atmosphere composed primarily of oxygen. Its surface is striated by cracks and streaks, whereas craters are relatively rare. It has the smoothest surface of any known solid object in the Solar System. The apparent youth and smoothness of the surface have led to the hypothesis that a water ocean exists beneath it, which could conceivably serve as an abode for extraterrestrial life. This hypothesis proposes that heat from tidal flexing causes the ocean to remain liquid and drives geological activity similar to plate tectonics. On 8 September 2014, NASA reported finding evidence supporting earlier suggestions of plate tectonics in Europa''s thick ice shell—the first sign of such geological activity on a world other than Earth. On 12 May 2015, scientists announced that sea salt from a subsurface ocean may be coating some geological features on Europa, suggesting that the ocean is interacting with the seafloor. This may be important in determining if Europa could be habitable for life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In December 2013, NASA reported the detection of "clay-like minerals" (specifically, phyllosilicates), often associated with "organic material" on the icy crust of Europa. In addition, NASA announced, based on studies with the Hubble Space Telescope, that water vapor plumes were detected on Europa and were similar to water vapor plumes detected on Enceladus, moon of Saturn.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Galileo mission, launched in 1989, provided the bulk of current data on Europa. No spacecraft has yet landed on Europa, but its intriguing characteristics have led to several ambitious exploration proposals. The European Space Agency''s Jupiter Icy Moon Explorer (JUICE) is a mission to Europa that is due to launch in 2022. NASA''s planned Europa Clipper mission will be launched in the mid-2020s.</p>', 'Jupiter', 1560.8, 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/X97Tna9Nlv_UG696DlOdUWxRjiwFjECl0fdmjSO0_xdk4P6bM7vDIToz27WsSk_mBut6VRudfXunux3UeXIBdw8gFbOlEgNkhKzMkv2d6_uRpP2sY7KvczTQM83ti1MtpAoir0i6Tou89_8sfY0C3flEEFwKcFnvTM641s8XrWRyq-QjlVIbm9MuUu11LteYxUSftFcV-1OXlspXvmdnAEmSseoq-Vh-XXLpGhE-z-7aK65HWb9JZezQx7xEf8BMI2UrvwcT6H1QagqGSZlyT51u_xzcre00VeOPzdf1XyCh3UMgr3ZCxn0R-eDFrYf1oQQVg1eSuVCkgvWAkzUMLlk7AEovSu9sPYDk5BKxQE0GpOIAT-VkOIc8CT5mUn0LLhozdNJEz53kyD7fFOvn_wkCWRV8tijfjD4Bg9BzKuYBd_VcUt19mDDJORbWlc2veluykc4ivlUqbwQ1p5AA8lIS9SPjcJU6DHiQqW_U5Z7WQV7Y9v6kLdnq8c7raVwqlSUkSZpWbIkeOGv7S3U-tozvjCPBpr-BhZx0JtHnZ-c=w198-h111-no', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/c69z3L-Ab5BVi73wTsyuiU6e7JMoiuS6IheV4PO4bHWEdN88yauH-y4Xm7LqddpuXMEH6ywWvDsjHdKv03fBMLRyzaC9rGlht1eEIz1_rKDk4MGGWgCmK4kp_QPIuSDsX2h8fCwLeo_OlsZ8e7yukstPMpCV6azkjThsFggq_x3l_h3kFi_RYIkd5XqxvQ_TJ9MgMLIRL06_GahDWBCOJP1ETg8QXP6ImNTXfO6ObidVbpbOHp7LReHy8ThZ2KAhKxLPM136QOfXcG5m4zh60tdb5EHjhMT24ROcesGqNmhCsbjlNSsruxmpGCn_c9MXflQ_tLQGbHeapLZcc4iHlQ77DFQi7lDERS0E5uloD1Hv7wVjK2Bx3P-VW_TRl-zXKKFcT4cPw6_rOnOJNZ84CAx1gNeiet2eQW3TokHV1hK_AflyBIJuZmF1YqhcTxqeWoaTmJ2IHwNrxTH-mzh19jUuPT_ofsQ42puvN720x-rdms_q2FXPKL0CIICsD2lvYEQUXst7YSboEP-8XXINSkRG1hjy_O20gD9ELSbCp48=w1081-h799-no,https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/5H1xB3mFkjvwnVw9Rw66MUFDIeHaTc5OBjzvEc5-Q4OoGJgAJvXskmaXWd-v2phxAD41Jam9sm9Ni4qJBDfwK2D5oRp2mBaHtIctGngmKeSD_P9SStVGSowqLCvP2jywftGr08S_IDwJn7-h29-WCHdA7ZlU-Gu5nxJrOfCQYvSLb2WGp3uOuwBgXdNCYDn0CeIDLXGurlxVUHLZOOIO0V7cnh01HEAZSak9JWtIpr_VVE-Bt3TKEyKkZUgs33gWQwtmZA37cqHsbaj0nxs