(2, 'Sirius', 8.6, 1.711, 'Canis Major', 'Sirius (/ˈsɪriəs/) is the brightest star (in fact, a star system) in the Earth''s night sky. With a visual apparent magnitude of −1.46, it is almost twice as bright as Canopus, the next brightest star. The name "Sirius" is derived from the Ancient Greek: Σείριος Seirios ("glowing" or "scorcher"). The system has the Bayer designation Alpha Canis Majoris (α CMa). What the naked eye perceives as a single star is actually a binary star system, consisting of a white main-sequence star of spectral type A1V, termed Sirius A, and a faint white dwarf companion of spectral type DA2, called Sirius B. The distance separating Sirius A from its companion varies between 8.2 and 31.5 AU.\r\n\r\n<p>Sirius appears bright because of both its intrinsic luminosity and its proximity to Earth. At a distance of 2.6 parsecs (8.6 ly), as determined by the Hipparcos astrometry satellite, the Sirius system is one of Earth''s near neighbors. Sirius is gradually moving closer to the Solar System, so it will slightly increase in brightness over the next 60,000 years. After that time its distance will begin to increase, but it will continue to be the brightest star in the Earth''s sky for the next 210,000 years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sirius A is about twice as massive as the Sun (M<sub>☉</sub>) and has an absolute visual magnitude of 1.42. It is 25 times more luminous than the Sun but has a significantly lower luminosity than other bright stars such as Canopus or Rigel. The system is between 200 and 300 million years old. It was originally composed of two bright bluish stars. The more massive of these, Sirius B, consumed its resources and became a red giant before shedding its outer layers and collapsing into its current state as a white dwarf around 120 million years ago.<p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sirius is also known colloquially as the "Dog Star", reflecting its prominence in its constellation, Canis Major (Greater Dog). The heliacal rising of Sirius marked the flooding of the Nile in Ancient Egypt and the "dog days" of summer for the ancient Greeks, while to the Polynesians in the southern hemisphere it marked winter and was an important star for navigation around the Pacific Ocean.</p>', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/ISZs0axmVkLsT5UDuXPpgvXFaW9SqWOYJlS5aLtG6UCg-zhczI5j5qCiwLsLz_gk3tzcAymmsoo0F5035MlnqweewY9j2GAx_994kYkcnoJE4aBJYhGRDU2BZaxAkPkhYD7R7Pj6PA92NLkFA2R23H8EEmNupj9-w33puqd5KfAerH37rNnt_6UjfR2rtaRQcQg-P5vZ-Ow7jcDyMo6kw0XwDrX_C-j9FdjTgM_ZgHxsaoSSJKH5wlKc6vphATTUzhvN4dMw9f-aERtetqU70kKtNfU9VOdpPNMf_CHwgpczKuRe2vATfRuQIaV87jovWqVPkuPHvcfdzIfCuDlwfVDqt4PIFZwGxriacHkz9-RSXoElQ7T5N-56B4qOIpPa8863rYR0tgKOA_elcxDyCVoCUGcMIiGr914kQs5Oauib0p_j_4OI1dko9MjKRYCdVHDW9kU0NZ-cBNl7J0i_PEZdRq73ZmrTSAKXaxHR3zPdGR2SBzQCFl7XlE-ARQvvL8kUjTJalkwd77cpAMFVlcf8phyn5OeRB7fZYMEnPFY=w198-h111-no', 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/q6qvCV2IIGmZcWoTXnLmd-PLvC9-D5jQYFiN8cSVOIX_O3g4fF46xYPok08XokTc1d-uAhHxBpbwNXEjdc6oQEBn03EuRb64o44q3I3Tt7wJ5AP5WDckpCpciwJ_nKRodcDsvoDdlg_HApcXtb3e14zo_b90Q4JZlECJwXigQWTyGOYxGH6JSmJ_fC9qElIZVo5ozRhKlhXYI0OQSJQ1v5-X2joDIx3Pjlr8eTbISgxddQwjyAqlqwbZAS_PgMJ8SSZHcmQh3OC2aNt1DzzVukDWl2qaGiGqkWEQsSvmnn4OdL_rigjKlh6W7CLrwoPyqUMpzFGPn4X7qm55ZGUlpfgAvSQpAXw9oWqPJi3TDyVMrGj-PAODiWWO_PEULUbH0GiAQnT4Kv5yJRMMoMs5W0mGKIG0OkX1okMSCFzEkIQ28fXnIKvp_KpByXbSwkoR8X736lTDYUpGsK7xgq3KhfnWuFyTCTDPVjA3C5tLrhmb9jwfuXJHeOHNDeu3pL775TJ39FxGjn7d-1ErJc-7gRazW0z5Rrw4pdHgc2qgbws=w369-h403-no,https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/PGwTSwJEl3IcmxsFiGEpeByrY5yUrm6_bO0tTEvscXZn7hzOlSaUlDiWpTZ4FVt1EWEd0mxV46eytM0rbKjTDRRYJZ8YCbsivGpCadl_7Twz4raFUlVJ87F8fvE3Tf_ADC-YyKdloRvQTD2VnHDn-g73cwn6cgCtdwVnT0Mi9Zozy3lz7uqYq04rE8N12-Tpa6pIGKQBTYBVjoZF8L6X2fwT1npACFYlx4mtnaM_36UseORkKumOmuBlGYB8W3VAh0fC0gh90-wqyUE23DtGqL2Kxf-yWoNt-JaBlRs_a07e7TCjsQJSEWzZHGEDwiAgqHZWgV5Y7lx0jkA-CxuFlaprfPDhBt2GPHL5BLfHY_qKefHaOkjqXWaaNW1b9fAf__TDMiHtJVm6U0zq5ib0RpImRriYo3RukUKzEpj-V5pqjuM2tHRLjBOyXtDpzBIwUeFyUNcIMOVwZetJXWQ8p3fnckfzDuG7UrgzoZ18tD31YqDg4cB1vPk6pJ0IADgm0pK3y7GEouAr9O8jd7GL6aj